Halve and toast @potato buns{2} in a hot pan.

Cut @fresh mozzarella{4%oz} into 1/2-inch slices; set aside four slices (eight slices
for 4) and dice remaining mozzarella into pieces.

In a #bowl{}, whisk together @mayonnaise{2%tbsp} and @Italian dressing{1.5%oz}.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

In a second bowl, combine @ground beef{10%oz}, @garlic powder{1%tsp},
@Italian seasoning{1%tbsp} (2 tsp for 4), salt (we used ½ tsp; 1 tsp for 4), and
pepper. Form into two patties (four patties for 4), each slightly wider than a
burger bun.

Drizzle @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a hot #pan{}. Add patties and cook to desired
doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

In the last ~{1-2%minutes} of cooking, top each patty with as much
@marinara{5%oz cup} as you like (reserve any remaining marinara for serving) and
mozzarella slices; cover pan to melt cheese.

> TIP: Be careful when adding the marinara—there may be some splattering in the pan!

Wash and dry produce.

To bowl with dressing mixture, add @mixed greens{4%oz}, @grape tomatoes{4%oz},
@shredded carrots{4%oz}, @sliced almonds{½%oz}, and diced mozzarella; toss to
combine.

> TIP: Plate salad as soon as you finish this step.

Spread toasted buns with as much @garlic herb butter{2%tbsp} as you like.

Fill buns with cheese-topped patties. Divide burgers between plates; serve with
salad and any remaining marinara on the side.

> Ground beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.